The Effect Silicon Valley Bank's Failure Had on Different Sectors of the Stock Market

DS4200 Lecture 20 - Tehani Cabour

Overview

The failure of the Silicon Valley Bank (SVB) on March 10th, 2023, marked the second greatest bank failure in the US since the 2008 recession. As this bank failure reached companies of all sectors, most students at Northeastern have had some personal story relating to the incident, whether it be their parent’s workplace or somewhere they have had a CO-OP. The recent string of events has led me to become interested in how the stock market has been impacted by SVB’s declaration of bank failure. This visualization will demonstrate the impact Silicon Valley Bank’s failure has had on the stock market by following the percent changes in adjusted closing stock prices for companies part of S&P500. To gather a large overview, I have decided to focus on S&P500 stocks, as it has a good spread of different sectors, and is often referenced in determining the overall state of the US stock market (and potentially the US economy). I have limited the timeline from a week prior to the incident (starting March 3rd, 2023) until about a week after the incident (ending March 16th, 2023). Two datasets are used in this analysis: Yahoo Finance’s Python library and a S&P500 companies CSV file from Datahub (https://datahub.io/core/s-and-p-500-companies). The reasoning behind choosing these two datasets is that while Yahoo Finance is a very reliable source of updated stock information, its stock information dataset is sometimes lacking in its Python library. The Datahub CSV file contains the S&P500 companies, as well as their company names and sectors, which would enable us to draw more connections between the bank failure and its impact. Upon cleaning the data, I have found that though the Yahoo Finance data has no issues, some of the tickers included in the CSV file have either been renamed or delisted. I have done some additional research on Yahoo Finance’s actual website to find which stocks have been renamed and removed those delisted from my dataset. It is also important to note that, because the stock market is closed on weekends, March 4th, 5th, 11th, and 12th are not included in the dataset.

Infographic

This infographic depicts the states of different sectors of the stock market a week leading to the failure of the Silicon Valley Bank (SVB), and a week after the event. Because this phenomenon had such a strong impact on the market, it is reasonable to conclude any dramatic changes in stock prices between March 3rd 2023 and March 16th 2023 are a direct result of SVB’s collapse. As a way to gauge the general health of the different sectors, this infographic includes data of only S&P500 company stocks (often referenced in determining the overall state of the US stock market). I found this event particularly interesting to depict for two main reasons: 1) it marks the second greatest bank failure in the US since the 2008 recession, and 2) the state of the stock market has been much more volatile ever since Covid-19, so seeing its response to such an event may help us better understand it. I hope users will gain a better understand about not just the bank failure in itself, but how widespread its impact has been on our economy, and how this reflects the fragile state of the financial market.

Data Visualization(s)

First Visualization

Average Percent Change in the Daily Stock Prices within Each Sector Across the Start of March 2023

To first have a general snapshot of the broad effects the bank’s failure has had on the stock market, I have decided to create a visualization depicting the average percent changes within each sector. As can be seen in the chart above, all sectors experienced a dip on March 10th (day of bank failure). The most noteworthy observation, however, is the sector most affected: the Financial sector. Although it is an unsurprising phenomenon, it is concerning to see how dramatic the drop is, especially when set against other sectors. For this visualization, I have decided to make an interactive line chart. The marks are lines, the qualitative channel is color (for the sectors), and the qualitative channel for both percent change and date are position (as it is most effective to demonstrate the evolution). I have decided to make the chart’s legend interactive to enable the user to select a line to emphasize. Without this function, the line chart can be hard to follow if the user were trying to follow one sector in particular, as the lines often cross. Color is used to demonstrate the different sectors as it is the simplest channel to discern the different lines.

Second Visualization

Percent Change in Daily Stock Prices Across the Start of March 2023 for Companies in the Financial Sector

After observing the dramatic effect the bank’s failure has had on the stock prices of other companies in the financial sector, I have decided to create an interactive line chart depicting the percent changes for each company in the financial sector within that timeframe. The chart shows the company names on hover and has a movable average bar (in a bright red to create a pop-out effect). It is unsurprising that SVB Financial (parent company of Silicon Valley Bank demonstrated by the orange- red line) has fallen so much (the only reason it hasn’t gotten to zero is due to yf maintaining the last closing price despite the stock volume reaching 0). However, thanks to this chart, we can draw conclusions on how other banks were affected. For instance, First Republic Bank (yellow line), has immensely tanked. Upon further research, this phenomenon is due to its similarity in clientele (tech industry), size (small/mid) , and location (prevalent in Boston) to SVB. On the other hand, financial electronic platforms (such as MarketAxess represented by the brown line) seems relatively unaffected by the event. For this visualization, I have chosen lines as marks, position as the quantitative channel (for both date and percent change in price), and color as qualitative channel. I found color to be the best channel to discern lines in lines charts of high volume. The interactive components are the hover function, which enables the user to read the company name if they hover above a point, and the interactive average bar (brushing selection). The average bar visualizes the average value within the selected interval, which helps the user gain some idea of the overall stock performance for the sector as a whole, and compare each line to that foundation.

Third Visualization

Error Bars Using Confidence Intervals for Daily Average Stock Prices for Each Sector Across the Start of March 2023

Finally, for my last visualization, I have chosen to create a error bars chart with confidence intervals. This not only gives a clearer image of the sector averages, but it as well demonstrates the how accurately those averages apply to the companies within the sectors. Longer bars mean that this is a greater variety in stock price changes between different companies in that same sector. The best example of this is the Financials sector. Given that some companies have reached levels of bankruptcy, while other financial companies remained relatively unaffected, it makes sense that its bar is the longest in the chart. Dots and lines are the marks used in this chart. The position is both used as the qualitative (sectors) and quantitative (percent change mean) channels. Confidence interval, however, has length as its qualitative channel. Between the short length of the bars and the small amount of sectors represented, I did not find there to be need of other visual channels, and believe that length and position are suitable for this kind of chart. The interactive component is a label on hover, including the confidence intervals and means for each bar, making the chart specific without looking crowded.
